h the dissolution of Siouxsie and the Banshees in 1996, the Creatures graduated from an occasional project to a full-time concern. The drum and voice duo released four studio albums: "Feast" in 1983, "Boomerang" in 1989, "Anima Animus" in 1999 and "Hái! " in 2003.', 'The Creatures (Australian band) | The Creatures were a garage rock band which formed in Mildura, Australia in 1965 as The Beagle Boys. They changed their name in February 1966 and relocated to Sydney where they were active during the mid- to late 1960s. The line-up included three Marcic brothers: Eric on guitar, Herman on bass guitar, and Rudolph on drums; together with Keith Matcham on lead vocals and Michael Parnis on rhythm guitar.', 'ʿAjā\'ib al-makhlūqāt wa gharā\'ib al-mawjūdāt | ʿAjā\'ib al-makhlūqāt wa gharā\'ib al-mawjūdāt, The Wonders of Creation (Arabic: عجائب المخلوقات و غرائب الموجودات\u200e \u200e , meaning "Marvels of creatures and Strange things existing") is book in Arabic and an important work of cosmography by Zakariya al-Qazwini who was born in Qazwin year 600 (AH)/1203.'], 'question': 'Which was formed first, The Creatures or This Picture?', 'reasoning': 'The context provided does not contain any information about a band or project named "This Picture". However, it does provide information about two bands named "The Creatures". The first band, "The Creatures", was formed in 1981 according to the context. The second band, also named "The Creatures", was formed in 1965 in Australia. Therefore, to answer the question, we would need to search for information about "This Picture" and compare its formation date with those of "The Creatures".', 'search_query': 'Formation year of the band "This Picture"'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Sheila Rabb Weidenfeld | Sheila Rabb Weidenfeld (born c. 1943) is a television producer and the former Press Secretary to First Lady Betty Ford and Special Assistant to President Gerald Ford. She is the author of the "“First Lady’s Lady,”" a book about her experiences in the Ford White House.', 'Sheila Widnall | Sheila Marie Evans Widnall (born July 13, 1938) is an American aerospace researcher and Institute Professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. She served as United States Secretary of the Air Force between 1993 and 1997, making her the first female Secretary of the Air Force and the first woman to lead an entire branch of the U.S. military in the Department of Defense.', "Susan Whitson | Susan Dryden Whitson was press secretary to First Lady Laura Bush, the wife of U.S. President George W. Bush. During the attacks of September 11th, she was flying from Washington to Milwaukee with Attorney General John Ashcroft. Prior to working at the White House, she was the Deputy Communications Director of the Bush-Cheney '04 campaign and the spokesperson for the President and Mrs. Bush's twin daughters, Barbara and Jenna Bush. Susan Whitson also worked for the FBI, the US Department of Justice and for Rep. Bob Riley (R-AL), the former governor of Alabama, and Rep. Bill McCollum (R-FL) on Capitol Hill. She was a high school English teacher at Hoover High School in Birmingham, Alabama. She attended Auburn University."], 'question': 'In which policy was this First Lady to whom Sheila Rabb Weidenfeld served as Press Secretary active?', 'reasoning': 'From the context provided, Sheila Rabb Weidenfeld served as the Press Secretary to First Lady Betty Ford. Betty Ford was the wife of Gerald Ford, who was the President of the United States. Therefore, we need to identify which policy Betty Ford was active in.', 'search_query': 'What were the key policies or areas of activity for Betty Ford during her time as First Lady?'}) (input_keys=None)]

